pipeline_messages.content:
You are an expert writing quality judge. You will evaluate three drafts
against a set of personalized rubric criteria. You also have access to the user's
recent conversation history for additional context about their preferences.

The three drafts are:
- Draft A = the **rubric-guided** draft (written following the user's rubric criteria)
- Draft B = the **generic** draft (written with no rubric — just competent writing)
- Draft C = the **original preference** draft (written from the user's stated preferences, before the rubric was created)

DRAFT A (rubric-guided):
Subject: Pre-Launch Checklist — Who Owns What

With the launch date locked, I know most of you are already working against a real deadline rather than an abstract one. This email is meant to make your planning easier, not add to the noise — so here's exactly who owns what, with no ambiguity.

Marcus owns QA sign-off. Priya owns legal review and the compliance checklist. Dev owns the deployment runbook and rollback plan. Simone owns external comms and the customer-facing release notes. If your name isn't here, you don't have a pre-launch deliverable.

Each owner has what they need from me. If something is missing, come directly to me by end of Thursday.

DRAFT B (generic):
Subject: Pre-Launch Ownership — Who's Got What

Team, now that we have a confirmed launch date, I want to make sure everyone knows exactly what they own on the pre-launch checklist so nothing slips through.

Jordan, you have final QA sign-off. Priya, all copy approvals run through you. Marcus, you're confirming the infrastructure is green by end of day Thursday. Lena, the client-facing assets are yours to finalize and distribute.

If your name isn't listed here, you're not on the hook for a deliverable — but I do need everyone available for the all-hands check-in Friday morning.

Thanks,
[Name]

DRAFT C (original preference):
Subject: Pre-Launch Ownership — Who's Doing What

Team,

With the launch date confirmed, I want to make sure every item on the pre-launch checklist has a clear owner — no gaps, no overlap.

I've assigned each of you a specific section based on your role. Please check the shared doc, find your name, and confirm you're good with your items by EOD Thursday. If something looks off or you're blocked, flag it then, not the day before launch.

One owner per task. If yours needs a second set of eyes, coordinate directly — don't loop the whole team.

Thanks,
[Name]

RUBRIC CRITERIA (the user's personalized writing quality criteria):
{
  "rubric": [
    {
      "name": "Information Sequencing",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "The order of beats is deliberate: acknowledgment of the reader's situation comes before the news, and a human-facing impact line precedes any logistics or detail blocks. Each section lands because of what came before it.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "empathy_before_news",
          "label": "Acknowledgment of the reader's situation appears before the key news or change is delivered"
        },
        {
          "id": "impact_line_before_details",
          "label": "A reader-facing impact line exists as its own beat before any logistics, bullet lists, or action items"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_afterthought_empathy",
          "label": "Empathy and acknowledgment do not appear only after the news, where they read as cleanup or afterthought"
        },
        {
          "id": "logical_arc",
          "label": "The overall sequence has a clear arc \u2014 context, news, impact, details, next step \u2014 without doubling back"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 1
    },
    {
      "name": "Reader-Centered Framing",
      "category": "Audience",
      "description": "The message is framed around the reader's reality \u2014 their disruptions, their stakeholder pressures, their planning \u2014 rather than justifying the sender's reasoning or the company's position. Impact is named from the audience's side.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "impact_from_reader_side",
          "label": "Impact and stakes are described in terms of what changes for the reader, not why the sender made the decision"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_sender_justification",
          "label": "Avoids framing that explains or defends the sender's reasoning as the emotional center of the message"
        },
        {
          "id": "acknowledges_real_friction",
          "label": "Names specific, concrete disruptions the reader is actually experiencing (not abstract sentiments)"
        },
        {
          "id": "logistics_serve_reader",
          "label": "Detail sections are framed as tools the reader can use, not status reports for the sender"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 2
    },
    {
      "name": "Specific Accountability",
      "category": "Content",
      "description": "People and owners are named specifically. Actions are directed to identifiable individuals, not generic placeholders or unnamed groups. Vague group-asks are replaced with clear ownership.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "named_owners",
          "label": "Anyone responsible for a task or deliverable is identified by name, not by placeholder or role"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_vague_group_asks",
          "label": "Action items are directed to specific people, not phrased as 'everyone figure it out'"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_redundant_contacts",
          "label": "There is no unnecessary multiplication of contact points \u2014 if one owner covers it, don't add a second"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 3
    },
    {
      "name": "Functional Density",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Every line does identifiable work. Sentences are not decorative \u2014 each one advances the message, provides usable information, or serves a distinct structural purpose. If a line can be cut without loss, it should be.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "every_line_earns_place",
          "label": "Each sentence has a clear function \u2014 no line exists purely for padding or transition"
        },
        {
          "id": "distinct_beats",
          "label": "Each section or paragraph handles a distinct beat; no two sections do the same job"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_redundant_information",
          "label": "Information is stated once, clearly, without rephrasing or restating the same point"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 4
    },
    {
      "name": "Direct, Non-Corporate Tone",
      "category": "Style",
      "description": "Tone is honest and human \u2014 direct without blaming, acknowledging without sugarcoating. Avoids language that reads like corporate communications, company all-hands, or PR framing.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "no_corporate_platitudes",
          "label": "Avoids stock phrases like 'thank you for your resilience' or 'commitment to getting this right'"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_blame_no_sugarcoat",
          "label": "Delivers difficult information without assigning blame or softening it with false positivity"
        },
        {
          "id": "human_not_performative",
          "label": "Empathy reads as genuine and specific, not as a performative gesture or obligatory acknowledgment"
        },
        {
          "id": "plain_direct_language",
          "label": "Uses plain, direct language rather than corporate or PR-style framing"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 5
    },
    {
      "name": "Clean, Decisive Endings",
      "category": "Structure",
      "description": "The message ends when the information ends. There is one clear next step or touchpoint, no competing actions, and no trailing sentiment or motivational closers.",
      "dimensions": [
        {
          "id": "single_next_step",
          "label": "The close contains exactly one clear next step or touchpoint, not multiple competing actions"
        },
        {
          "id": "no_motivational_closer",
          "label": "No motivational, sentimental, or 'all-hands' style closing lines after the final action"
        },
        {
          "id": "ends_at_information",
          "label": "The email stops when there is nothing left to communicate \u2014 no trailing filler"
        }
      ],
      "priority": 6
    }
  ],
  "version": 2,
  "source": "criteria_classification",
  "writing_type": "internal team communications",
  "user_goals_summary": "Writes direct, reader-centered team updates where every line earns its place. Prioritizes acknowledging the real impact on the audience over justifying the sender's decisions. Values precise structural sequencing, clean endings, and specific accountability \u2014 rejects corporate platitudes, motivational closers, and vague group-asks.",
  "coaching_notes": "This user iterates by subtraction \u2014 they approve structure quickly but spend most revisions cutting, reordering, and consolidating. Never ask 'do you want this warmer?' \u2014 they consistently remove warmth that feels performative. Their north star is: does every element serve the reader, and does the message end the moment the information does?"
}

