The user also said: "A is the strongest — it acknowledges the real deadline context first (reader-framing, not sender-framing), delivers the ownership list cleanly, and ends with a concrete single action. The closing line is forward-looking without being sentimental. C is solid — named owners, clear tasks, and I like that it explicitly releases non-listed people from deliverable anxiety. The 'everyone available Friday' ask is a minor group-ask but it's low-stakes enough to live with. B is the weakest by a margin — 'Please check the shared doc and find your name' is almost the definition of an ambiguous group ask dressed up as structure. It assumes a shared doc exists and puts the burden on recipients to self-identify their tasks. That's exactly the 'everyone please review' problem I was trying to avoid, just slightly reworded."


WHY THREE DRAFTS:
The rubric was built from the user's original stated preferences. The preference-based draft acts as a **comparison signal**: by scoring both the rubric-guided draft and the preference-based draft against the same rubric criteria, we can see where the rubric successfully captures the user's intent (rubric draft scores equal or higher) and where it falls short (preference draft scores higher). The generic draft is a baseline — if it scores highest, the criterion isn't adding value at all.

